10. Ea res nunc ayitur ipsa] This pas- sage has given more trouble than almost any other in Terence, in consequence of the variation of the manuscripts. In many editions the speeches are so arranged as to make sense quite hopeless. In some edi- tions after this line there follows ‘Erravi: res acta: quanta de spe decidi,’ which is entirely wanting in the Vatican and Bem- bine manuscripts and some of the earliest editions3 and as Bentley well remarks, in- ter-feres with the sense: for Menedemus is not made to discover his mistake till Chremes has explained the whole matter. The insertion of such a line here would make ‘imo’ quite unmeaning.
